				<p>A policy tells us what control to apply given a state. If the state-space is formulated well for the RL agent then distinctly different scenarios may look the same in the state-space and yield the same behavior. This is called generalization and is desirable when done correctly. The robot will have a maximum speed based on the speed of it's control loop. The learned behavior will not necessarily be to slow down. If the reward is inversely related to the length of time of the run then the agent would be inclined to max out it's speed with respect to the speed of it's control loop.</p>
